You said:
can you talk me through how to connet a new workspace (called codestar_blog) on my VS Code with my new repo https://github.com/christinalicence/django-blog. The folder is empty on vs code, I've added some user stories in github
ChatGPT said:
Got it 👍 Let’s get your local VS Code workspace (codestar_blog) connected to your GitHub repo (django-blog). Since your folder is empty, we’ll essentially clone or pull down the repo into it. Here’s the step-by-step walkthrough:

1. Open the folder in VS Code
Open VS Code.

Go to File > Open Folder... and select your empty codestar_blog folder.

This is now your working directory.

2. Open the terminal
In VS Code, open the integrated terminal:

View > Terminal (or shortcut: <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>`</kbd>).

3. Initialise Git (if not already done)
Run:

git init
This makes your folder a Git repo (it will create a .git folder).

4. Connect to GitHub repo
Run:

git remote add origin https://github.com/christinalicence/django-blog.git
Check it worked:

git remote -v
You should see:

origin  https://github.com/christinalicence/django-blog.git (fetch)
origin  https://github.com/christinalicence/django-blog.git (push)
5. Pull down what’s on GitHub
Since you already created some user stories in GitHub, we want to pull them into your empty folder.

Run:

git pull origin main
⚠️ Note: If your repo uses master instead of main, swap main with master.

6. Start working
Now your local codestar_blog folder should have all the files from GitHub.
When you add code, you can commit and push back:

git add .
git commit -m "Your message here"
git push origin main
✅ That’s it — your VS Code workspace is now connected to your GitHub repo.

Would you like me to also set you up with the GitHub VS Code extension (so you can push/pull via buttons instead of the terminal), or do you prefer sticking with the command line?

You said:
I've set up a venv, but it doesn't seem to be activated. what do i need to do
ChatGPT said:
Nice one getting a venv set up 👌 The bit that often trips people up is actually activating it. Let’s check you’re on the right track.

1. Where did you create the venv?
Usually in your project folder you’d run something like:

python3 -m venv venv
This creates a folder called venv inside codestar_blog.

2. Activating it
It depends on your OS and shell:

On Mac/Linux (bash/zsh):
source venv/bin/activate
On Windows (PowerShell):
.\venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
On Windows (cmd.exe):
venv\Scripts\activate.bat
3. How to check it’s active
Your terminal prompt should change to show (venv) at the start.

Run:

which python
(Mac/Linux) or

where python
(Windows).
It should point to the Python inside your venv.

4. VS Code Integration
Even if you activate manually, it’s good to tell VS Code which interpreter to use:

Open the Command Palette (<kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>P</kbd> or <kbd>Cmd</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>P</kbd> on Mac).

Search Python: Select Interpreter.

Choose the one from your codestar_blog/venv.

👉 Question for you: do you want the venv to auto-activate when you open VS Code, or are you happy running source venv/bin/activate (or the Windows equivalent) each time?

