(.venv) christinaward@Christinas-MacBook-Air codestar_blog % git push
fatal: The current branch master has no upstream branch.
To push the current branch and set the remote as upstream, use

    git push --set-upstream origin master

To have this happen automatically for branches without a tracking
upstream, see 'push.autoSetupRemote' in 'git help config'.
ChatGPT said:
Perfect, that error just means Git doesn’t know yet which remote branch your local master should sync with on GitHub. Easy fix 🚀

Since your repo is already connected to origin, you just need to set the upstream branch once:

git push --set-upstream origin master
After that, you’ll be able to just do:

git push
and

git pull
without specifying the branch each time.

⚠️ One thing to double-check:

Your GitHub repo might be using main as the default branch instead of master.

Run:

git branch -a
to see what branch names exist locally and remotely.

If GitHub’s branch is main, but your local is master, you’ve got two choices:

Switch your local to main:

git branch -M main
git push --set-upstream origin main
(this is the modern convention)

Or just keep using master and push it — GitHub will then have a master branch as well.

👉 Do you want me to walk you through renaming your local master to main so it lines up with GitHub’s defaults, or would you rather just push master as-is?

You said:
Can I delete the 'main' one on my repo and keep using master
ChatGPT said:
Yep — you can absolutely do that 👍 If you prefer sticking with master, you just need to tidy up your GitHub repo so master is the default branch and main is removed.

Here’s how:

1. Push your local master to GitHub
If you haven’t already:

git push --set-upstream origin master
2. Make master the default branch on GitHub
Go to your repo on GitHub.

Click Settings → Branches.

Under Default branch, change it from main to master.

3. Delete the main branch
Still in the GitHub UI:

Go to the Branches tab.

Find main.

Click the trashcan/delete icon to remove it.

✅ After that, your repo will only have master, and every git push from your machine will go straight to it.

👉 Do you want me to give you the commands for deleting main from the command line instead of doing it in the GitHub UI?

