You said:
what's the terminal command to update your requirements file when a new package is intalled
ChatGPT said:
Great question 🙌 That’s something you’ll do a lot in a Django project.

Once you’ve installed a new package in your virtual environment with:

pip install package-name
you can update your requirements.txt by running:

pip freeze > requirements.txt
A few tips:
Run this inside your venv (make sure you see (.venv) in your terminal).

That command will overwrite the existing requirements.txt with the full list of installed packages and versions.

If you want to just append one new package instead of rewriting the whole file, you can do:

pip freeze | grep package-name >> requirements.txt
👉 Do you want me to also show you how to set up a workflow so that requirements.txt updates automatically whenever you install something (instead of remembering to run the command manually)?

You said:
Bad Request (400)
ChatGPT said:
Got it — you’re seeing a “Bad Request (400)” error, right? That’s a generic Django error that usually means the request is malformed, and the most common cause when you’re just starting out is a missing or incorrect ALLOWED_HOSTS setting.

Quick check:
Open your settings.py file in your Django project and look for:

ALLOWED_HOSTS = []
When ALLOWED_HOSTS is empty, Django only accepts requests from localhost. If you’re accessing your app differently (e.g., 127.0.0.1, 0.0.0.0, or through a server), Django will reject it with a 400 error.

Fix:
While developing, you can make it permissive:

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ["*"]
Or, more safely:

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ["localhost", "127.0.0.1"]
Then restart your server:

python manage.py runserver
Other possible causes:
URL typo → check you’re visiting the right path (e.g., /admin/ not /admins/).

Cookies/session corruption → try an incognito window or clear cookies.

Mismatched ports → make sure you’re on the same port Django is running (default 8000).

👉 Are you running the server locally on your Mac (python manage.py runserver), or is this error showing up after you deployed it somewhere (like PythonAnywhere, Render, or Heroku)? That’ll help narrow it down.

