Thanks for sharing the full traceback — this one’s clear 👌

The error is here in your settings.py:

'default': dj_database_url.parse(os.environ.get("postgresql://...."))
What went wrong
os.environ.get() is used to fetch environment variables by name.

But you’ve given it your entire connection string, not an environment variable key.

So Django is trying to parse None (since no env var exists with that long name), which breaks.

✅ Correct way with dj-database-url
You have two options:

Option 1: Hardcode the URL directly (quick test)
DATABASES = {
    'default': dj_database_url.parse(
        "postgresql://neondb_owner:npg_CcFdpU3jsPE4@ep-curly-dew-agty1kbb.c-2.eu-central-1.aws.neon.tech/aids_wasp_thump_969382"
    )
}
Option 2: Use an environment variable (recommended)
Add the URL to your .env file (if you’re using python-decouple or django-environ), or export it in your shell:

export DATABASE_URL="postgresql://neondb_owner:...@.../aids_wasp_thump_969382"
In settings.py:

DATABASES = {
    'default': dj_database_url.parse(os.environ.get("DATABASE_URL"))
}
This is cleaner and keeps secrets out of version control.

⚡ Quick fix to unblock you: replace the line in your settings.py with Option 1 (hardcoded). Then re-run:

