Thanks for the traceback 👌 This one means dj_database_url is being asked to parse an empty string (or None).

The key bit:

'default': dj_database_url.parse(os.environ.get("DATABASE_URL"))
👉 os.environ.get("DATABASE_URL") is returning None, because you haven’t set that environment variable yet. That’s why dj_database_url blows up with KeyError: ''.

✅ How to fix
Option 1: Hardcode (quick test)
Replace with:

DATABASES = {
    'default': dj_database_url.parse(
        "postgresql://neondb_owner:npg_CcFdpU3jsPE4@ep-curly-dew-agty1kbb.c-2.eu-central-1.aws.neon.tech/aids_wasp_thump_969382"
    )
}
That should let python3 manage.py migrate run immediately.

Option 2: Proper way (using environment variables)
Install python-dotenv (or use django-environ, both are fine).

pip install python-dotenv
Create a .env file in your project root:

DATABASE_URL=postgresql://neondb_owner:npg_CcFdpU3jsPE4@ep-curly-dew-agty1kbb.c-2.eu-central-1.aws.neon.tech/aids_wasp_thump_969382
Update settings.py to load it:

from dotenv import load_dotenv
load_dotenv()

DATABASES = {
    'default': dj_database_url.parse(os.environ.get("DATABASE_URL"))
}
Restart your shell (or reload .env) and run:

python3 manage.py migrate
⚡ Recommended: go with Option 2 — it keeps secrets out of version control and makes deployment easier later.

