You successfully committed all your changes and pushed them to GitHub, but one thing to note: your commit includes your entire virtual environment (.venv/). That’s why you see thousands of insertions like:

create mode 100644 .venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/...
Why that’s a problem
.venv can be huge (several MBs) and is not meant to be in Git.

You usually only track requirements.txt to recreate the environment elsewhere.

Committing the venv makes your repo unnecessarily large and can cause conflicts.

How to fix it
Add .venv to .gitignore

Create or edit a file named .gitignore in your project root:

# Python virtual environment
.venv/
__pycache__/
*.pyc
Remove the .venv from Git history

Run:

git rm -r --cached .venv
git commit -m "Remove virtual environment from repository"
git push
--cached removes the files from Git without deleting them locally.

Your local venv stays intact; only Git stops tracking it.

Keep requirements.txt updated

pip freeze > requirements.txt
git add requirements.txt
git commit -m "Update requirements"
git push
This is all you need to recreate the venv on another machine:

python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
