ChatGPT said:
I tried opening the link you gave for your Heroku app (/blog) — got an Internal Error. That means something is going wrong on the server side.

Here are some likely causes & steps you can take to debug and fix it:

🔎 Possible Causes
Database not configured properly
If your Heroku app’s database connection (e.g. NeonDB or Heroku Postgres) isn’t set up or the environment variable for the DB URL is missing/incorrect, Django will fail during a request.

SECRET_KEY / DEBUG misconfiguration
If DEBUG = False in production but you haven’t set up ALLOWED_HOSTS correctly, or your SECRET_KEY wasn’t set securely, Django can error out.

Missing static files setup
If static files aren’t collected or served (e.g. python manage.py collectstatic not run, or static file storage not properly configured), trying to load templates might break in weird ways.

Missing migrations
If you didn’t run migrations on the Heroku instance, or there's a mismatch between your local migration files and what’s deployed.

Dependencies issue
Maybe some package is missing or the version is wrong in requirements.txt, causing runtime errors in production.

Code errors
Something in view logic, templates, or settings that only kicks in in the production environment.

🛠 Steps to Debug / Fix
Here’s a checklist to go through:

Check Heroku logs

heroku logs --tail --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
Watch for errors thrown when accessing /blog. The traceback will often point to what’s broken.

Check environment variables on Heroku

Make sure DATABASE_URL is set correctly.

Make sure any needed secret keys (e.g. SECRET_KEY, maybe for OAuth etc.) are set.

If using something like dj_database_url, that env var needs to be correct.

Run migrations on Heroku

heroku run python manage.py migrate --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
Collect static files
If you have static files (CSS, images etc.), run:

heroku run python manage.py collectstatic --noinput --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
Check ALLOWED_HOSTS in settings.py
Make sure your Heroku domain is in ALLOWED_HOSTS, e.g.

ALLOWED_HOSTS = ['practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b.herokuapp.com', 'localhost', '127.0.0.1']
DEBUG temporarily
If safe, you can momentarily turn on DEBUG = True on Heroku (but be careful — do this only temporarily). That might show a detailed error page so you can see what’s going wrong. Then revert to False.

Dependencies
Double check your requirements.txt is correct and deployed. If you recently added something new, ensure it’s been installed. Sometimes Heroku has a mismatch.

