DATABASES

'default': dj_database_url.parse(os.environ.get("DATABASE_URL"))
If DATABASE_URL isn’t set on Heroku, this will blow up → KeyError: ''.

On Heroku, the DATABASE_URL is injected automatically if you’ve added the Heroku Postgres add-on.

If you’re using NeonDB instead, you must manually set DATABASE_URL in Heroku’s config vars.

Static files

Currently, you only have:

STATIC_URL = 'static/'
On Heroku, Django won’t serve static files unless you configure STATIC_ROOT and run collectstatic.

✅ Fixing your settings for Heroku
Here’s a safer, production-ready version:

from pathlib import Path
import os
import dj_database_url

if os.path.isfile('env.py'):
    import env

BASE_DIR = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

# Secret key
SECRET_KEY = os.environ.get('SECRET_KEY', 'dev-secret-key')  # fallback for local dev

DEBUG = 'DEVELOPMENT' in os.environ  # set DEVELOPMENT=True in local .env

ALLOWED_HOSTS = [
    '127.0.0.1',
    'localhost',
    'practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b.herokuapp.com',
]

# Database
DATABASES = {
    'default': dj_database_url.parse(os.environ.get("DATABASE_URL"))
}

# Static files
STATIC_URL = 'static/'
STATIC_ROOT = BASE_DIR / 'staticfiles'
🛠 Steps you should take now
Set Heroku config vars

heroku config:set SECRET_KEY='your-long-secret-key' --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
heroku config:set DATABASE_URL='your-neon-or-heroku-db-url' --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
Collect static files

heroku run python manage.py collectstatic --noinput --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
Run migrations

heroku run python manage.py migrate --app practice-my-blog-fd3393450c3b
👉 After this, your /blog page should load without a 500 error.

